Feature Significance and Feature Selection

Feature Selection with Partial F test

From EDA, we decided there is no multicollinearity in the predictors. We also found only Age, Experience, and Work_Hours_Per_Week seem to be correlated with performance score. So we will compare the full model with all features with the reduced model with only these three predictors, using partial F test.

MLR_full <- lm(Performance_Score ~ ., data = perf_train)
MLR_reduced <- lm(Performance_Score ~ Age + Experience + Work_Hours_Per_Week , data = perf_train)
# summary(MLR_reduced)
# summary(MLR_full)
anova(MLR_reduced, MLR_full)
## Analysis of Variance Table

## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1

p-value is 0.01078, indicating the subset of coefficients are statistical significant at alpha = 0.05 level. So we have to reject the null hypothesis that the coefficients for those predictors are equal to zero.

But with n = 8000, which is a large number and may cause inflated significance in predictors.

Handling Inflated Statistical Significance

“Inflated” Statistical Significance

## Approach: Subsample 10% of the initial data sample & repeat 100 times

count = 1
n = nrow(perf)
B = 100
ncoef = dim(summary(MLR_full)$coeff)[1]
pv_matrix = matrix(0,nrow = ncoef,ncol = B)

while (count <= B) {
  subsample = sample(n, floor(n*0.1), replace=FALSE)
  subdata = perf[subsample,]
  submod = lm(Performance_Score ~ .,data=subdata)
  pv_matrix[,count] = summary(submod)$coeff[,4]
  count = count + 1
}

# Count pvalues smaller than 0.01 across the 100 (sub)models
alpha = 0.01
pv_significant = rowSums(pv_matrix <= alpha)
pv_significant
##  [1]   1 100   0 100   0   0   1   3   0   1   0   5   1   0   0   2   1   1   1
## [20]   1   1   4   0 100   1   1   1   0   1   3
## Which regression coefficients are statistically significant?
idx_scoef = which(pv_significant>=95)

In the first three steps, All AIC have significant drops. But after Experience + Work_Hours_Per_Week + Age are added, no more significant drops in AIC when new features are added, aligns with the previous finding of feature significance.

Start: AIC=42067.41 Performance_Score ~ 1

Step: AIC=39633.1 Performance_Score ~ Experience

Step: AIC=38306.68 Performance_Score ~ Experience + Work_Hours_Per_Week

Step: AIC=36864.12 Performance_Score ~ Experience + Work_Hours_Per_Week + Age

Step: AIC=36860.73 Performance_Score ~ Experience + Work_Hours_Per_Week + Age + Work_Life_Balance

Based on group LASSO, most coefficients were shrinked to zero or close to zero, except three: Age, Experience, and Work_Hours_Per_week. This findings aligned with our correlation analysis in EDA, and significant analysis with 100 times iterative sub sampling.

This concludes the work in feature selection. Moving forward we will focus on the 3 predictors identified above.

                  data = perf_train,
                  method = "rf",
                  trControl = train_control,
                  tuneGrid = tune_grid,

# define function for accuracy measure
mse_fun <- function(pred,dat){mean((pred-dat)^2)}
mae_fun <- function(pred,dat){mean(abs(pred-dat))}
mape_fun <- function(pred,dat){mean(abs(pred-dat)/abs(dat))}
pm_fun <- function(pred,dat){sum((pred-dat)^2)/sum((dat-mean(dat))^2) }
ci_fun <- function(pred.lwr,pred.upr,dat){
  sum(dat<pred.lwr | dat>pred.upr)/length(dat) }

pred_fun <- function(model,perf_test){ 
  pred = predict(model, perf_test) 
  mse_model =  mse_fun(pred, perf_test$Performance_Score) 
  mae_model =  mae_fun(pred, perf_test$Performance_Score)
  mape_model = mape_fun(pred, perf_test$Performance_Score)
  pm_model  = pm_fun(pred, perf_test$Performance_Score)  
      pred_meas = c(mse_model,mae_model, mape_model, pm_model) 
   return(pred_meas)
}  
fitted_MLR_full = pred_fun(cv_MLR_full, perf_train)
fitted_MLR = pred_fun(cv_MLR, perf_train)
fitted_MLR_inter = pred_fun(cv_MLR_inter, perf_int_train)
fitted_tree = pred_fun(cv_tree, perf_train)
fitted_forest = pred_fun(cv_forest, perf_train)
fitted_forest_tuned = pred_fun(rf_model, perf_train)
fitted_xgb = pred_fun(cv_xgb, perf_train)
fitted_xgb_tuned = pred_fun(xgb_model1, perf_train)
